FordGoBike Data Exploration¶

by Hiver¶

Overview¶

In this investigation of the Ford GoBike System, I'm most interested in figuring out users habits, inclus:
  • When are the rush time of renting bike?
  • Where are their favorite places ?
  • How far they usually go ?
  • How long they take the trips ?
  • Is there different habits between subscriber and occasional customers?

Dataset Overview¶

- Ford GoBike is the Bay Area's bike share system with 700 bikes and 70 stations and will grow to 7,000 across San Francisco and San Jose. Riders can unlocked the bike from one station and returned to any other station.The bikes are available for use 24 hours/day, 7 days/week, 365 days/year and riders have access to all bikes in the network when they become a member or purchase a pass.

- In this investigation, I download the data in 7 consecutifs months from 9/2019 - 3/2020. It includes 1698486 rows of data with 15 features. Half of them are in numerics, and half are in object. I just take a sample of 16984 rows to work with to ensure the data enough large but also not hard to computing.

Distribution of usage time of one bike in one session¶

  • The renting time each session follow the normal distribution. Almost riders take a short trip in 10 minutes, it's far from the limit of 30 minutes and only 5% exceed that limit. The red line is the limit of quantile 95%

The rush renting time¶

  • It's clearly that February receives the highest number of renting.

  • The second highest is January, right after the winter. It seems user prefer to rent in the months with cool and cold climat (From Sep - Mars) and few or no renting during hot season (from Avril - August)

  • Contrary to what I thought, week days receive more renting than weekend

  • There are 2 peeks of renting a day : From 8-9h and 17-18h

Bike sharing and rental access method of differents user types¶

  • It can be seen that if user subscribes, they will rent more frequently
  • User prefer using app than clipper and they don't really like bike sharing for all trip
  • Although these factors don't drive people to rent or not but if we make things more convenient as users like and good marketing strategies, we can keep and increase the number of users

Does subscriber usually rent longer than occasional customers ?¶
    

  • From the boxplot, we can see the renting duration of occasional customers is slightly longer than subscribers. 
    • 

  • The violinplot shows that subscribers have a renting time more stable than occasional customers (almost people rent with the mean duration while with occasional customers, the renting time varies more)
    •

Weekly usage between customers and subscribers¶
    

  • In general, they have the same habit, more frequent in week days than during weekend. 
    • 

  • However, interestingly, in peak season and rush hours, subscribers are nearly double the occasional users while in low season, their numbers differ slightly. It seems the company should marketing new users in low season :)
    •

How does the hourly usage vary during weekdays for customers and subscribers?¶
    

  • Subscribers use the system heavily on work days i.e. Monday through Friday whereas customers ride a lot on weekends, especially in the afternoon. Many trips concentrated around 8-9am and 17-18pm on work days for subscribers when used for work commute
    • 

  • Customers tend to use more in the late afternoon around 17pm Monday to Friday. Other than usage purpose and habit, it may also have to do with the traffic situation around these rush hours in the area.
    •

customers = df.query('user_type == "Customer"')
ct_counts = customers.groupby(['day_of_week', 'time_in_day']).size()
ct_counts = ct_counts.reset_index(name='count')
ct_counts = ct_counts.pivot(index='day_of_week', columns='time_in_day', values='count')
sb.heatmap(ct_counts, cmap='rocket_r');
plt.title('Customer', loc='right');
plt.xlabel('Hour of Day');
plt.ylabel('Day of Week');

plt.subplot(2, 1, 2)
subscribers = df.query('user_type == "Subscriber"')
st_counts = subscribers.groupby(['day_of_week', 'time_in_day']).size()
st_counts = st_counts.reset_index(name='count')
st_counts = st_counts.pivot(index='day_of_week', columns='time_in_day', values='count')
sb.heatmap(st_counts, cmap='rocket_r');
plt.title('Subscriber', loc='right');
plt.xlabel('Hour of Day');
plt.ylabel('Day of Week');
plt.suptitle('Hourly Usage during Weekdays for Customers and Subscribers');
